WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hello, I'm Ella Kaye. I'm a research software engineer, an R package developer and a mother.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
This is the very first photo of my child.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:18.000
I was so happy and excited to be pregnant that I did what surely any self-respecting R package developer would do.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
I wrote myself a package to keep track of dates and medications in my pregnancy.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I could do things like call the howfar function that would print out the progress of my pregnancy

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
and it could do the calculation because I had hardcoded my due date into my package.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
The package could do other things as well and it was useful to me so I thought it might be useful for others.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:46.000
I decided to generalise and release the package but I wanted to make sure, as it was for me in my version of the package,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
that it was easy to use and that it felt personal as well.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:56.000
But mostly I wanted to make sure that the package was a pleasure to use.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
So today I'm going to introduce the pregnancy package, the general version,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
and also provide some tips and tricks that I think make a package a pleasure to use in general.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
In particular I'm going to talk about options and the null coalescing operator,

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.000
about rlang and cli for nicely formatted and informative messages,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
and using utility and helper functions.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So here's the pregnancy package.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Just like you could in my private version, you can call howfar

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:32.000
and you will see a progress message about the pregnancy with a given due date addressed in the second person.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
You are so many weeks pregnant.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Let's try that again for a completely different pregnancy.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Again, howfar, no arguments, different due date, still the appropriate calculations,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
this time addressed in the first person, I am.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
What if you want to use this package not about you, but say,

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
see your partner's name reflected in the messages?

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
That's fine too, you can do that, and you can also do more complex date calculations

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
that you might get in online pregnancy apps.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
So for example, howfar a pregnancy is going to be on a given date,

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
or the date when a particular pregnancy milestone is going to be reached.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So how does it work?

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
How can we make the package a pleasure to use by making it easy to call these functions

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
without needing to specify these arguments like the due date and the person

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
that aren't going to change each time you use the package?

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
This is the function signature for howfar,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.000
and you'll see that the due date and person arguments are both set by default to null.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And then in the function code, we have the following,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
because we do need to have a due date to do the calculations.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
So first of all, on line 1, it's going to look to see whether the due date

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
has been passed as an argument to the function.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And if it has, it's good, we're good, we're done on line 1.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
But if it's null, as it will be by default,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
the null coalescing operator at the end of line 1 kicks in,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
and it was going to look for an option to see if that's been set,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
the pregnancy due date option.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
If it has, again, we're good, we're done on line 2,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.000
but if not, that option is null, and the null coalescing operator at the end of line 2 kicks in,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
and we look for line 3, in which case we're going to get an error message

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
as generated by the datestop utility function.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So what does that do?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Well, we're using Arlang and CLI, and it's going to inform us exactly what the problem is,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
and then it's going to tell us how we can fix it.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
You can set the due date argument.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
In the second bullet, it says you can set the pregnancy.dueDate option using a helper function

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
provided by the package, the setDueDate function,

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
or the recommended approach is to set options pregnancy.dueDate in your R profile,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
because if you do that, you just need to do that once,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
and then in every R session in the future, that R will find that due date,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
and you can call any of the functions in the pregnancy package,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
and you will never have to specify your due date again,

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
because it will pick it up from that option,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
and you get a link to the documentation to provide more details.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So if this sounds like a pure street and the package will be useful to you now

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
or sometime in the future or for someone you know,

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
then check out the pregnancy package,

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
but even if not, I hope I have provided you with some useful tips and tricks

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
to help you think about how you can make your package a pleasure to use.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Thank you very much.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
www.ottobock.com

